WATCHER-DEATH after a push-heavy gm session is DESIGNED self-healing, not a crash (gm-method). Witnesses of the recycle (not crash): .shutdown-reason.json empty, .watcher.log ends clean with no panic/exit line, prior boot_reason 'planned-restart-after-peer-stale-takeover'. Mechanism: every push that lands a new wrapper sha cascade-refreshes ~/.gm-tools, and the supervisor's wrapper-sha-drift check recycles the running watcher to load it; peer-takeover (new-wrapper watcher kills the old-wrapper holder) + manual recovery boots add more. The supervisor respawns on a 10s poll / 30s stale threshold (supervisor.js POLL_INTERVAL_MS/STATUS_STALE_MS) -- a sane latency; lowering it would kill legitimately-busy watchers (a long codesearch index rebuild advertises busy_until ~360s and must be honored, not reaped). So a session that pushes many wrapper changes will see repeated ~30-50s watcher-stale windows; the prescribed handling is the boot-probe re-boot (which does NOT trip a deviation -- own:0 confirmed), and the watcher stabilizes once pushes stop. Not a bug to fix. RELATED: a clean audit fire (own deviations 0, ccsniff git/search/glyph/bash zero) can still involve many recovery boots without any own deviation -- mechanical re-boot is correct recovery, never escalate to the user.